WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.375 --> 00:00:05.360
MALE SPEAKER: So welcome
to Talks at Google,

00:00:05.360 --> 00:00:07.720
to this afternoon we're
very thrilled to host

00:00:07.720 --> 00:00:11.430
Greg Ferenstein, who is a
former political journalist

00:00:11.430 --> 00:00:13.730
for TechCrunch, where,
among his other skills,

00:00:13.730 --> 00:00:16.960
he taught mathematics to
journalists, which is always

00:00:16.960 --> 00:00:18.430
an important thing to do.

00:00:18.430 --> 00:00:19.990
And he's here
speaking to us today

00:00:19.990 --> 00:00:24.560
about his latest thesis,
which arose out of some Medium

00:00:24.560 --> 00:00:27.780
posts and some articles for
TechCrunch, "Silicon Valley's

00:00:27.780 --> 00:00:30.670
Political End Game,"
so this strange mixture

00:00:30.670 --> 00:00:33.460
of libertarianism and
progressivism we have here.

00:00:33.460 --> 00:00:34.460
And what does that mean?

00:00:34.460 --> 00:00:35.590
Where is it going?

00:00:35.590 --> 00:00:39.070
How does it impact the local
and national issues we face?

00:00:39.070 --> 00:00:41.560
So with that, please join me
in welcoming Greg to Google.

00:00:41.560 --> 00:00:42.060
Thanks.

00:00:47.172 --> 00:00:48.880
GREGORY FERENSTEIN:
Thanks for having me.

00:00:48.880 --> 00:00:52.070
I think I kind of want
to thank you guys,

00:00:52.070 --> 00:00:56.520
because I think 70% of all
of my internet experience

00:00:56.520 --> 00:00:59.280
is at Google itself--
Google Docs, Google,

00:00:59.280 --> 00:01:00.540
Google Maps, everything.

00:01:00.540 --> 00:01:02.260
My internet experience
and digital life

00:01:02.260 --> 00:01:03.310
is basically Google.

00:01:03.310 --> 00:01:05.239
So thank you.

00:01:05.239 --> 00:01:06.750
I appreciate it, guys.

00:01:06.750 --> 00:01:13.790
In 1981, the "Ottawa Citizen"
newspaper reported on a story

00:01:13.790 --> 00:01:16.890
from a University of
Carelton professor

00:01:16.890 --> 00:01:19.630
who claimed that if "teachers
don't stand up to the growing

00:01:19.630 --> 00:01:23.020
invasion of computers
in the classroom,

00:01:23.020 --> 00:01:24.700
there's a good
chance that literacy

00:01:24.700 --> 00:01:29.000
will disappear in 10 years."

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:31.280
Obviously, these were
not prophetic words.

00:01:31.280 --> 00:01:36.690
When I first began researching
the politics and philosophy

00:01:36.690 --> 00:01:39.200
of breakthrough innovators,
I started with what I knew

00:01:39.200 --> 00:01:40.020
wasn't.

00:01:40.020 --> 00:01:42.080
And I knew it wasn't pessimism.

00:01:42.080 --> 00:01:44.230
You would dedicate
your life to trying

00:01:44.230 --> 00:01:48.520
to improve the future if you
thought the outlook was bleak.

00:01:48.520 --> 00:01:51.580
And indeed, when I then
began systematically

00:01:51.580 --> 00:01:54.230
to interview
breakthrough innovators

00:01:54.230 --> 00:01:58.060
about their philosophy,
what was core to them,

00:01:58.060 --> 00:02:01.430
first and foremost,
above all else,

00:02:01.430 --> 00:02:04.770
they describe
themselves as optimists.

00:02:04.770 --> 00:02:08.449
We're working with two
different devices here.

00:02:08.449 --> 00:02:11.620
Wikipedia founder,
Jimmy Wales, "I'm

00:02:11.620 --> 00:02:15.070
a pathologically
optimistic person."

00:02:15.070 --> 00:02:17.262
Mark Zuckerberg,
"I'm an optimist.

00:02:17.262 --> 00:02:19.220
I think you need to be,
to be an entrepreneur."

00:02:19.220 --> 00:02:21.490
"I may be the most
optimistic person I know.

00:02:21.490 --> 00:02:23.440
I mean I'm incredibly
optimistic.

00:02:23.440 --> 00:02:25.380
I'm optimistic,
arguably, to a fault,

00:02:25.380 --> 00:02:30.000
especially in terms of new
idea," Marc Andreessen.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:32.440
Steve Jobs, "I'm an
optimist in the sense

00:02:32.440 --> 00:02:35.590
that I believe humans are noble
and honorable, and some of them

00:02:35.590 --> 00:02:36.830
are really smart.

00:02:36.830 --> 00:02:41.340
I have a very optimistic
view of individuals."

00:02:41.340 --> 00:02:43.610
At first, I dismissed
this optimism

00:02:43.610 --> 00:02:47.240
as just kind of like hippie
frou-frou Silicon Valley.

00:02:47.240 --> 00:02:49.970
But then I learned
this optimism was just

00:02:49.970 --> 00:02:56.450
a rhetorical wrapper around very
specific business strategies

00:02:56.450 --> 00:02:58.452
and political policies.

00:03:04.500 --> 00:03:07.220
The motivation
originally behind this

00:03:07.220 --> 00:03:09.600
was that technologists,
all of a sudden,

00:03:09.600 --> 00:03:14.620
are becoming very influential,
at least according to "Forbes."

00:03:14.620 --> 00:03:19.310
Over 80% of billionaires on
the Forbes 400 list under 40

00:03:19.310 --> 00:03:21.580
come from technology.

00:03:21.580 --> 00:03:23.250
So whatever these
folks believe is

00:03:23.250 --> 00:03:27.159
going to exert an extraordinary
amount of influence

00:03:27.159 --> 00:03:27.825
over the future.

00:03:31.130 --> 00:03:33.220
So I wanted to answer
three questions.

00:03:33.220 --> 00:03:36.250
One, does the optimism of
information technologists

00:03:36.250 --> 00:03:37.430
have a unique worldview?

00:03:37.430 --> 00:03:39.180
Is it just that they're
good at technology

00:03:39.180 --> 00:03:40.670
and they happened
to do politics,

00:03:40.670 --> 00:03:43.820
or are they somehow combined?

00:03:43.820 --> 00:03:47.370
Does this worldview help
them make technology?

00:03:47.370 --> 00:03:49.370
That is, is there something
about their politics

00:03:49.370 --> 00:03:50.970
and their vision
for the future that

00:03:50.970 --> 00:03:53.380
is behind and almost
a prerequisite

00:03:53.380 --> 00:03:56.860
for billion-dollar ideas?

00:03:56.860 --> 00:03:59.850
And the last is,
is this worldview

00:03:59.850 --> 00:04:02.970
shared by just a small number
of very rich and very successful

00:04:02.970 --> 00:04:06.880
people, or is it part of a
broader political movement?

00:04:06.880 --> 00:04:11.470
The answer to all of
these, I think, is yes.

00:04:11.470 --> 00:04:13.330
And because I'm
attention deficit

00:04:13.330 --> 00:04:14.760
and I assume my
audience is too, I

00:04:14.760 --> 00:04:17.564
will just go ahead and tell
you my thesis before I go on

00:04:17.564 --> 00:04:18.439
with the explanation.

00:04:21.450 --> 00:04:23.830
The world has
gotten more complex.

00:04:23.830 --> 00:04:26.570
As a result, it's given rise
to the knowledge economy.

00:04:26.570 --> 00:04:28.720
The knowledge
economy has empowered

00:04:28.720 --> 00:04:32.600
a novelty-seeking
personality that

00:04:32.600 --> 00:04:36.200
has an extreme optimism
in information alone

00:04:36.200 --> 00:04:38.370
to solve problems.

00:04:38.370 --> 00:04:41.770
This is built on a
growing demographic

00:04:41.770 --> 00:04:45.060
of college-educated,
urbanized professionals, who

00:04:45.060 --> 00:04:48.540
represent an entirely
new political category.

00:04:48.540 --> 00:04:50.895
They are pro-government
and pro-market

00:04:50.895 --> 00:04:52.520
but believe the
government's role isn't

00:04:52.520 --> 00:04:56.040
to regulate capitalism, but
to invest in capitalism,

00:04:56.040 --> 00:04:59.790
to accelerate change
by investing directly

00:04:59.790 --> 00:05:06.570
in citizens to be more educated,
entrepreneurial, and civic.

00:05:06.570 --> 00:05:10.050
If you take away nothing
else, very simple, betting

00:05:10.050 --> 00:05:11.750
that information
will make the future

00:05:11.750 --> 00:05:14.740
has become a very
profitable belief system.

00:05:14.740 --> 00:05:16.430
And that essentially
is why optimists

00:05:16.430 --> 00:05:17.530
will inherit the earth.

00:05:17.530 --> 00:05:20.730
The rest is explanation.

00:05:20.730 --> 00:05:23.630
So starting with
the first question,

00:05:23.630 --> 00:05:25.640
what do these folks believe?

00:05:25.640 --> 00:05:27.400
The best explanation
actually came

00:05:27.400 --> 00:05:31.380
from the patron of this
organization, Eric Schmidt.

00:05:31.380 --> 00:05:34.280
He said, "there's a particular
religion that we all represent,

00:05:34.280 --> 00:05:36.420
and it goes something like this.

00:05:36.420 --> 00:05:38.330
If you take a large
number of people

00:05:38.330 --> 00:05:40.240
and you empower them
with communication tools

00:05:40.240 --> 00:05:43.630
and opportunities to be
created, society gets better.

00:05:43.630 --> 00:05:47.240
The combination of empowerment,
innovation, and creativity

00:05:47.240 --> 00:05:49.760
will be will be our solution.

00:05:49.760 --> 00:05:53.310
And that is a religion
in-of-itself."

00:05:53.310 --> 00:05:55.310
So the folks who make
breakthrough technologies

00:05:55.310 --> 00:05:57.770
and help them along
are cognizant that they

00:05:57.770 --> 00:06:00.940
have a distinct world view.

00:06:00.940 --> 00:06:06.490
So when I delved deeper into
Eric's and other people's idea

00:06:06.490 --> 00:06:09.340
that somehow citizens,
just through empowerment,

00:06:09.340 --> 00:06:11.050
could make the world
a better place,

00:06:11.050 --> 00:06:15.390
I found that their philosophy
was founded on two main ideas.

00:06:15.390 --> 00:06:21.550
First, as Reid Hoffman
told me, "if you're

00:06:21.550 --> 00:06:23.440
working towards
progress, your future

00:06:23.440 --> 00:06:25.480
will be better
than your present."

00:06:25.480 --> 00:06:29.010
That is change is
inherently good.

00:06:29.010 --> 00:06:32.940
The very nature of change
makes things better.

00:06:32.940 --> 00:06:35.610
Now, change can often be
bad over the short term.

00:06:35.610 --> 00:06:37.640
You can have a bad
20 or 30 years even.

00:06:37.640 --> 00:06:40.320
But eventually, if
you just keep trying,

00:06:40.320 --> 00:06:43.110
if you just keep
changing and disrupting,

00:06:43.110 --> 00:06:45.730
eventually things get better.

00:06:45.730 --> 00:06:48.390
This is the first
tenant of optimism,

00:06:48.390 --> 00:06:50.810
or at least described
by Silicon Valley.

00:06:50.810 --> 00:06:52.790
So then I took
what I was learning

00:06:52.790 --> 00:06:55.550
from Reid Hoffman and
other folks, and I said,

00:06:55.550 --> 00:06:58.510
is this just the very
wealthy in Silicon Valley,

00:06:58.510 --> 00:07:02.790
or is it technologists
more broadly?

00:07:02.790 --> 00:07:06.200
So I'm a former writer for a
tech blog called TechCrunch.

00:07:06.200 --> 00:07:09.920
They have a database of every
single startup founder ever.

00:07:09.920 --> 00:07:13.130
I found their email addresses
and randomly emailed

00:07:13.130 --> 00:07:15.910
them to take a battery of
40 political psychology

00:07:15.910 --> 00:07:19.170
questions, which
became what I think

00:07:19.170 --> 00:07:22.190
is the first representative
political opinion poll of what

00:07:22.190 --> 00:07:24.380
Silicon Valley believes.

00:07:24.380 --> 00:07:27.600
And I peppered them with
some of these statements.

00:07:27.600 --> 00:07:33.270
Indeed, when you ask, is change
inherently good or productive

00:07:33.270 --> 00:07:36.370
over the long term,
80% of tech founders

00:07:36.370 --> 00:07:38.560
say yes-- near unanimity.

00:07:38.560 --> 00:07:42.670
That number is unheard of in
political opinion polling.

00:07:42.670 --> 00:07:44.670
You rarely get numbers that big.

00:07:44.670 --> 00:07:46.850
When I compare
that same question

00:07:46.850 --> 00:07:51.240
to a survey done of the general
population, only 48% of people

00:07:51.240 --> 00:07:57.220
agreed that change inherently
over the long run is good.

00:07:57.220 --> 00:08:00.536
Now, this gets into why
the Valley's generally

00:08:00.536 --> 00:08:02.910
kind of considered libertarian--
this kind of free market

00:08:02.910 --> 00:08:04.010
ideology, anything goes.

00:08:04.010 --> 00:08:06.110
Let's change as
quickly as possible.

00:08:06.110 --> 00:08:09.110
When you compare tech
founders with Libertarians

00:08:09.110 --> 00:08:12.080
and Democrats, they
look like Libertarians

00:08:12.080 --> 00:08:13.930
on a couple big issues.

00:08:13.930 --> 00:08:17.027
They're not as big a
fans of labor unions.

00:08:17.027 --> 00:08:19.110
They tend to believe that
labor unions, especially

00:08:19.110 --> 00:08:21.680
teachers unions, tend to
protect the status quo

00:08:21.680 --> 00:08:24.970
and prevent organizations from
experimenting and piloting

00:08:24.970 --> 00:08:27.140
new things and moving into
the future very quickly.

00:08:27.140 --> 00:08:29.960
So about 29% of
tech founders think

00:08:29.960 --> 00:08:33.179
that labor unions are
good for the economy,

00:08:33.179 --> 00:08:35.309
and 21% of Libertarians.

00:08:35.309 --> 00:08:37.700
On the flip side,
they're radically

00:08:37.700 --> 00:08:40.320
pro-free trade-- NAFTA, TPP.

00:08:40.320 --> 00:08:43.650
They want capitalism everywhere.

00:08:43.650 --> 00:08:47.950
And that's where this myth that
the Silicon Valley is generally

00:08:47.950 --> 00:08:50.010
Libertarian comes from.

00:08:50.010 --> 00:08:53.600
That would be true, except for
the fact that Silicon Valley,

00:08:53.600 --> 00:08:58.080
as a whole, is arguably the
most liberal industry on planet

00:08:58.080 --> 00:08:59.180
Earth.

00:08:59.180 --> 00:09:04.070
83% of donations in the
2012 presidential election

00:09:04.070 --> 00:09:07.170
from top tech firms, like
Google, Facebook, and Amazon,

00:09:07.170 --> 00:09:11.200
went to Obama
versus Romney-- 83%.

00:09:11.200 --> 00:09:14.170
If you look at all
donations back to 2008

00:09:14.170 --> 00:09:17.090
from every single tech
founder and investor,

00:09:17.090 --> 00:09:19.380
63% went to Democrats.

00:09:19.380 --> 00:09:22.450
In my survey of tech
founders, about 7%

00:09:22.450 --> 00:09:24.830
identify as Republican.

00:09:24.830 --> 00:09:27.120
So clearly, if we
want to understand

00:09:27.120 --> 00:09:29.550
what tech founders
and Silicon Valley

00:09:29.550 --> 00:09:31.800
believes, thinking that
they're Libertarian

00:09:31.800 --> 00:09:33.110
was missing something.

00:09:33.110 --> 00:09:36.880
Why are they such a big fan
of the Democratic party?

00:09:36.880 --> 00:09:41.330
And this I learned,
when a Libertarian icon

00:09:41.330 --> 00:09:43.930
in the Senate, Rand
Paul, announced

00:09:43.930 --> 00:09:47.380
his presidential candidacy
and came to San Francisco.

00:09:47.380 --> 00:09:48.784
And he got up on stage.

00:09:48.784 --> 00:09:49.700
He was really excited.

00:09:49.700 --> 00:09:53.704
He wanted to warm up the
crowd, and he led with this.

00:09:53.704 --> 00:09:54.550
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:09:54.550 --> 00:09:59.085
-Is there anybody out here from
the leave-me-alone coalition?

00:09:59.085 --> 00:10:00.023
Not that many.

00:10:00.023 --> 00:10:01.097
[END PLAYBACK]

00:10:01.097 --> 00:10:02.180
GREGORY FERENSTEIN: Right?

00:10:02.180 --> 00:10:07.120
He said, is anyone out here from
the leave-me-alone coalition?

00:10:07.120 --> 00:10:12.600
No one clapped, and
it was really awkward.

00:10:12.600 --> 00:10:15.420
Leave me alone, get
government out of my life

00:10:15.420 --> 00:10:18.360
is central to the
Libertarian philosophy.

00:10:18.360 --> 00:10:21.184
And yet it was not
popular in San Francisco.

00:10:23.850 --> 00:10:26.240
This led me to do
some more questioning.

00:10:26.240 --> 00:10:28.850
So one of the central
tenants of Libertarianism

00:10:28.850 --> 00:10:31.780
is that there is a
conflict between government

00:10:31.780 --> 00:10:34.030
and citizens.

00:10:34.030 --> 00:10:36.790
On the flipside,
Democrats tend to believe

00:10:36.790 --> 00:10:40.710
that there's a conflict between
citizens and big corporations.

00:10:40.710 --> 00:10:44.850
The richer corporations
get, the less citizens have.

00:10:44.850 --> 00:10:50.890
Tech founders, as a
group, overwhelmingly

00:10:50.890 --> 00:10:53.190
believe that there's is no
conflict between business,

00:10:53.190 --> 00:10:56.270
corporations, or citizens.

00:10:56.270 --> 00:11:01.240
At 61%, they say everyone
has a role in society,

00:11:01.240 --> 00:11:05.440
and they can all work
together, compared to just 20%

00:11:05.440 --> 00:11:06.050
of the public.

00:11:08.660 --> 00:11:11.170
They have an optimism
that collectivism

00:11:11.170 --> 00:11:13.090
and interdependence is possible.

00:11:13.090 --> 00:11:15.740
When I dug deeper
into that theory,

00:11:15.740 --> 00:11:19.295
I learned that a popular term
in the Valley is what's called

00:11:19.295 --> 00:11:22.940
"non-zero sum economy--"
a non-zero sum economy.

00:11:22.940 --> 00:11:25.694
The idea that you can build
things that benefit people.

00:11:25.694 --> 00:11:27.610
Even if some people
benefit a little bit more,

00:11:27.610 --> 00:11:29.910
you raise the tide for everyone.

00:11:29.910 --> 00:11:33.120
The core of this
popular non-zero sum

00:11:33.120 --> 00:11:36.080
meme in Silicon
Valley is that what

00:11:36.080 --> 00:11:38.320
is good for you is good for me.

00:11:38.320 --> 00:11:41.620
What is bad for you
is also bad for me.

00:11:41.620 --> 00:11:46.590
So I asked this question,
does everything people

00:11:46.590 --> 00:11:49.510
do, including their
personal decisions,

00:11:49.510 --> 00:11:52.520
like whether to be
educated or eat healthy,

00:11:52.520 --> 00:11:54.980
affect enough other
people to justify

00:11:54.980 --> 00:11:56.920
government intervention?

00:11:56.920 --> 00:12:01.980
A near majority, 49% of
founders believed that.

00:12:01.980 --> 00:12:06.860
Only 20% of Libertarians
and 60% of Democrats.

00:12:06.860 --> 00:12:09.020
That is they think
interdependence

00:12:09.020 --> 00:12:15.120
is part of society,
that we are connected.

00:12:15.120 --> 00:12:19.580
And so now we have a working
definition of optimism.

00:12:19.580 --> 00:12:21.430
There is always
a better solution

00:12:21.430 --> 00:12:23.033
that benefits more people.

00:12:28.300 --> 00:12:30.470
I think most reasonable
people, at this point,

00:12:30.470 --> 00:12:33.960
would be asking
themselves, what is

00:12:33.960 --> 00:12:37.180
the connection between
technology and politics?

00:12:37.180 --> 00:12:39.332
You've shown me a
lot of correlations.

00:12:39.332 --> 00:12:42.830
But what do the two have
to do with each other?

00:12:42.830 --> 00:12:44.570
I kind of want to
make the case to you

00:12:44.570 --> 00:12:52.530
that technology is if not
mostly political, inherently

00:12:52.530 --> 00:12:54.700
political.

00:12:54.700 --> 00:12:58.970
If you build a missile,
you build it for a reason.

00:12:58.970 --> 00:13:01.140
You're trying to
protect the country.

00:13:01.140 --> 00:13:03.970
Hawkish people, who are
fearful of other countries

00:13:03.970 --> 00:13:08.850
or terrorists, build
military technologies.

00:13:08.850 --> 00:13:10.840
If any of you guys
know any Bitcoin folks,

00:13:10.840 --> 00:13:12.990
the anonymous
crypto currency that

00:13:12.990 --> 00:13:15.290
is an alternative to
money, the community

00:13:15.290 --> 00:13:17.600
started out hyper Libertarian.

00:13:17.600 --> 00:13:20.830
They wanted to free the
economy from the confines

00:13:20.830 --> 00:13:24.740
of the government and its
control over the cash supply

00:13:24.740 --> 00:13:27.730
So what I did is I
found a way to predict

00:13:27.730 --> 00:13:32.870
someone's political ideology
from the products they built.

00:13:32.870 --> 00:13:37.350
I looked at every single public
political donation, Federal

00:13:37.350 --> 00:13:41.820
Elections Commission, and I
matched that to tech founders.

00:13:41.820 --> 00:13:45.090
And I found that,
indeed-- you might have

00:13:45.090 --> 00:13:46.760
troubles reading the slide.

00:13:46.760 --> 00:13:49.070
But this is the
political orientation

00:13:49.070 --> 00:13:52.760
grouped by startup category.

00:13:52.760 --> 00:13:55.130
If you work in finance,
in cyber security,

00:13:55.130 --> 00:13:57.370
you're more likely to
be a hawkish Republican

00:13:57.370 --> 00:14:00.820
or a Libertarian, which is
kind of what we thought.

00:14:00.820 --> 00:14:04.510
The most liberal category
in all of startup land,

00:14:04.510 --> 00:14:08.840
or one of them,
social networking.

00:14:08.840 --> 00:14:10.560
Why is that the case?

00:14:10.560 --> 00:14:15.030
Why is a social network
political at all?

00:14:15.030 --> 00:14:16.660
And that's what I
find fascinating,

00:14:16.660 --> 00:14:20.450
because the actual
politics of Silicon

00:14:20.450 --> 00:14:23.170
Valley and technologists
and tech workers

00:14:23.170 --> 00:14:25.890
are so distinct from our
traditional categories,

00:14:25.890 --> 00:14:28.850
we don't even recognize
that a social network has,

00:14:28.850 --> 00:14:30.960
in fact, a policy analog.

00:14:30.960 --> 00:14:37.120
The way I want to show you that
is the differences between My

00:14:37.120 --> 00:14:38.810
Space and Facebook.

00:14:38.810 --> 00:14:42.000
If you can remember all the
way back in internet history,

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:46.050
back to 2006, My Space
was king of kings.

00:14:46.050 --> 00:14:47.890
And they had an idea
that social networking

00:14:47.890 --> 00:14:49.310
was about expression.

00:14:49.310 --> 00:14:54.470
On the left here, you
see-- or it's you're right.

00:14:54.470 --> 00:14:55.669
You see a My Space page.

00:14:55.669 --> 00:14:56.960
You could do whatever you want.

00:14:56.960 --> 00:14:58.084
You could make it annoying.

00:14:58.084 --> 00:15:00.000
You could have auto play music.

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:01.130
My Space didn't care.

00:15:01.130 --> 00:15:02.210
They encouraged this.

00:15:02.210 --> 00:15:04.340
When pornographic
stars were kicked off

00:15:04.340 --> 00:15:07.160
of earlier social networks,
they invited them on My Space.

00:15:07.160 --> 00:15:08.530
Do whatever you want.

00:15:08.530 --> 00:15:10.855
It is a Libertarian
expression paradise.

00:15:14.650 --> 00:15:18.430
And the culture of
their users ate it up.

00:15:18.430 --> 00:15:21.800
There was a phrase that went
viral, before we kind of knew

00:15:21.800 --> 00:15:25.875
what viral meant, in 2006
on My Space that said,

00:15:25.875 --> 00:15:27.120
"don't judge me."

00:15:27.120 --> 00:15:30.840
This is what people plastered
all over their profiles.

00:15:30.840 --> 00:15:32.800
It was so popular
that it spawned

00:15:32.800 --> 00:15:36.440
its own kind of gaudy t-shirt
and like rhinestone, the

00:15:36.440 --> 00:15:40.230
Don't Judge Me t-shirt line.

00:15:40.230 --> 00:15:46.240
Zuckerberg and co had
a different philosophy.

00:15:46.240 --> 00:15:47.870
Zuckerberg said,
"on My Space people

00:15:47.870 --> 00:15:50.130
got to do whatever they
wanted on their profile.

00:15:50.130 --> 00:15:54.020
We always thought
people would share more,

00:15:54.020 --> 00:15:55.980
if we didn't let them
do whatever they wanted,

00:15:55.980 --> 00:16:00.660
because we gave
them some order."

00:16:00.660 --> 00:16:03.000
Facebook had a North Star.

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:05.090
Sheryl Sandberg,
"Mark really does

00:16:05.090 --> 00:16:07.490
believe very much
in transparency

00:16:07.490 --> 00:16:10.130
and the vision of an open
society and an open world,

00:16:10.130 --> 00:16:12.317
and so he wants to
push people that way."

00:16:12.317 --> 00:16:14.150
So one of the early
things that Facebook did

00:16:14.150 --> 00:16:16.060
was they did auto
tagging of photos,

00:16:16.060 --> 00:16:18.450
and they eventually turned
that into the newsfeed.

00:16:18.450 --> 00:16:21.660
And if you remember, there
was a massive backlash.

00:16:21.660 --> 00:16:23.220
Zuckerberg personally
had to make

00:16:23.220 --> 00:16:25.405
a statement on the
front page of Facebook,

00:16:25.405 --> 00:16:26.530
or in people's [INAUDIBLE].

00:16:26.530 --> 00:16:27.622
He's like, I get it.

00:16:27.622 --> 00:16:28.830
You're worried about privacy.

00:16:28.830 --> 00:16:30.150
You're worry about
what's going on.

00:16:30.150 --> 00:16:31.320
But we have this
vision for the world,

00:16:31.320 --> 00:16:33.190
and we're going to continue
doing the newsfeed.

00:16:33.190 --> 00:16:34.670
And we're going
to continue trying

00:16:34.670 --> 00:16:37.040
to push people to
share more information,

00:16:37.040 --> 00:16:39.180
because he believed--
and this is often

00:16:39.180 --> 00:16:42.284
made fun-- that just getting
people to share cat videos

00:16:42.284 --> 00:16:43.700
or what they're
doing at a wedding

00:16:43.700 --> 00:16:45.970
or what they believe
or an article, just

00:16:45.970 --> 00:16:50.610
sharing information was a way to
make the world a better place.

00:16:50.610 --> 00:16:52.840
Doesn't seem very political.

00:16:52.840 --> 00:16:59.370
We know it is because one
of Facebook's first users

00:16:59.370 --> 00:17:05.829
was this guy, Harvard University
Professor Robert Putnam.

00:17:05.829 --> 00:17:10.220
Putnam became famous for
this idea of social capital.

00:17:10.220 --> 00:17:12.670
It's a theory that says
the best way to improve

00:17:12.670 --> 00:17:14.930
the governance of a city,
to make people healthier,

00:17:14.930 --> 00:17:18.430
to make economies more equal,
to make the bureaucracy more

00:17:18.430 --> 00:17:21.819
efficient is simply to
get people to hangout more

00:17:21.819 --> 00:17:24.940
on an informal basis--
bowling leagues,

00:17:24.940 --> 00:17:28.510
book clubs, rotary clubs.

00:17:28.510 --> 00:17:33.320
He found this in a
25-year-long study of Italy.

00:17:33.320 --> 00:17:35.870
And he wanted to know why
some sections in the north,

00:17:35.870 --> 00:17:38.940
like Amelia, were
much more prosperous

00:17:38.940 --> 00:17:40.750
and equal and healthy.

00:17:40.750 --> 00:17:43.690
And after 25 years of
studying every variable

00:17:43.690 --> 00:17:47.630
in political science, he
found one simple pattern.

00:17:47.630 --> 00:17:49.440
In the north, there
was more community.

00:17:49.440 --> 00:17:53.670
Specifically, people
just hung out more.

00:17:53.670 --> 00:17:57.640
That simple fact
of Northern Italy

00:17:57.640 --> 00:17:59.922
made them a much better society.

00:18:02.440 --> 00:18:06.120
And now governments around the
world-- sometimes with the UN--

00:18:06.120 --> 00:18:10.420
it is a policy, a public policy,
to get people to hang out

00:18:10.420 --> 00:18:12.600
more on an informal basis.

00:18:12.600 --> 00:18:14.770
Social capital as
a political theory

00:18:14.770 --> 00:18:17.170
has been replicated
dozens of times, sometimes

00:18:17.170 --> 00:18:18.160
experimentally.

00:18:18.160 --> 00:18:21.294
They find out if you
share informal things,

00:18:21.294 --> 00:18:24.390
things get better.

00:18:24.390 --> 00:18:30.900
Facebook was the technological
manifestation of that policy,

00:18:30.900 --> 00:18:34.300
and a rather optimistic
policy at that.

00:18:34.300 --> 00:18:36.440
You want the world
to get better?

00:18:36.440 --> 00:18:38.550
Just have people talk more.

00:18:38.550 --> 00:18:42.910
Ultimately, it's an
informational philosophy.

00:18:42.910 --> 00:18:45.770
People share information
about government services

00:18:45.770 --> 00:18:48.400
or what people are doing wrong
or right in their neighborhood,

00:18:48.400 --> 00:18:50.570
and they also exchange empathy.

00:18:50.570 --> 00:18:51.897
They get to know each other.

00:18:58.740 --> 00:19:01.890
So if Silicon Valley
represents an entirely new

00:19:01.890 --> 00:19:06.060
political category,
people often ask me,

00:19:06.060 --> 00:19:12.330
what does this look like in
an actual policy, modern day?

00:19:12.330 --> 00:19:15.330
Google's backyard,
San Francisco.

00:19:15.330 --> 00:19:18.000
One of the distinct
beliefs that I learned

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:19.940
about Silicon Valley
was they believed

00:19:19.940 --> 00:19:27.630
that cities, bringing people
to cities, was a moral good.

00:19:27.630 --> 00:19:31.560
Often the San Francisco
housing crisis

00:19:31.560 --> 00:19:34.919
is often kind of couched
in terms of tech people

00:19:34.919 --> 00:19:36.460
just wanting cheaper
rent, and Google

00:19:36.460 --> 00:19:39.532
not having that have to pay
higher salaries because that's

00:19:39.532 --> 00:19:40.990
the only way that
their workers can

00:19:40.990 --> 00:19:42.766
afford to live close to campus.

00:19:42.766 --> 00:19:45.140
And if you're not familiar
with the San Francisco housing

00:19:45.140 --> 00:19:47.330
crisis, although I
assume most folks in here

00:19:47.330 --> 00:19:49.460
are-- or the Bay Area
housing crisis, for those

00:19:49.460 --> 00:19:53.710
watching online--
only 8% of housing

00:19:53.710 --> 00:19:55.760
is now affordable
in San Francisco

00:19:55.760 --> 00:19:58.250
because the city has tried
to protect its suburbs

00:19:58.250 --> 00:20:01.270
and won't allow buildings
to get taller or more dense.

00:20:01.270 --> 00:20:04.070
They've just
literally restricted

00:20:04.070 --> 00:20:07.240
a lot of dense buildings.

00:20:07.240 --> 00:20:08.990
Even if you can't buy
a home, median rents

00:20:08.990 --> 00:20:11.480
have skyrocketed
about $4,000 a month.

00:20:11.480 --> 00:20:14.590
Thousands of people have
been evicted from their homes

00:20:14.590 --> 00:20:18.040
from landlords who
see that they can now

00:20:18.040 --> 00:20:21.980
sell a relatively inexpensive
home for over $1 million or $2

00:20:21.980 --> 00:20:24.380
million.

00:20:24.380 --> 00:20:27.000
So as a result, you have
this massive conflict

00:20:27.000 --> 00:20:32.080
between technologists and some
renters who want to build more,

00:20:32.080 --> 00:20:34.824
and critics who say that
Google and tech companies

00:20:34.824 --> 00:20:37.240
and the rest of the creative
class that are coming in just

00:20:37.240 --> 00:20:38.365
want to take over the city.

00:20:42.290 --> 00:20:48.170
For 6,000 years of
technological history,

00:20:48.170 --> 00:20:53.680
cities have been the birth place
for information technology.

00:20:53.680 --> 00:21:01.800
Writing likely happened around
the time of Mesopotamia,

00:21:01.800 --> 00:21:07.040
when people gathered for the
first time in such large groups

00:21:07.040 --> 00:21:09.140
that they began to
have grain surpluses,

00:21:09.140 --> 00:21:11.550
and they couldn't account
for what everyone had.

00:21:11.550 --> 00:21:13.590
So they had cuneiform
tablets, and they

00:21:13.590 --> 00:21:15.020
made little tick marks.

00:21:15.020 --> 00:21:17.060
And that's how they
were able to keep track

00:21:17.060 --> 00:21:20.430
of who had what food and items.

00:21:20.430 --> 00:21:23.970
Complexity,
especially in cities,

00:21:23.970 --> 00:21:26.650
is the birthplace of many
information technologies,

00:21:26.650 --> 00:21:29.450
and it's been that
way for 6,000 years.

00:21:29.450 --> 00:21:31.570
So to believe in
cities isn't just

00:21:31.570 --> 00:21:34.220
to believe you
want cheaper rent,

00:21:34.220 --> 00:21:35.870
is to believe that
one of the best

00:21:35.870 --> 00:21:40.085
things you can do for humanity
is to bring them to cities.

00:21:43.570 --> 00:21:48.730
This is what San Francisco looks
like as an affordable city.

00:21:48.730 --> 00:21:54.510
That's a simulation I did based
on econometric estimates of San

00:21:54.510 --> 00:21:57.420
Francisco with almost double
the housing stock it has now--

00:21:57.420 --> 00:22:02.140
200,000 more units.

00:22:02.140 --> 00:22:04.630
Now we know that,
I think-- well,

00:22:04.630 --> 00:22:06.910
I've made the case that
information technologists,

00:22:06.910 --> 00:22:09.300
Silicon Valley, and
urbanized professionals

00:22:09.300 --> 00:22:11.530
have a distinct
political category.

00:22:11.530 --> 00:22:14.151
And we know what it kind
of looks like in policy.

00:22:17.040 --> 00:22:19.620
The title of the talk
is "Why Optimists Will

00:22:19.620 --> 00:22:26.440
Inherit the Earth."

00:22:26.440 --> 00:22:29.870
It turns out that
the dividing line,

00:22:29.870 --> 00:22:32.400
at least within the
Democratic Party,

00:22:32.400 --> 00:22:35.640
over people who are more
optimistic about change,

00:22:35.640 --> 00:22:37.590
a little bit more
collectivist in orientation,

00:22:37.590 --> 00:22:40.370
a bigger fan of free
trade, and investment

00:22:40.370 --> 00:22:42.300
orientation of
government happens

00:22:42.300 --> 00:22:43.750
to be college education.

00:22:43.750 --> 00:22:46.120
The more college
educated you are,

00:22:46.120 --> 00:22:50.340
the more you tend to
believe in this philosophy.

00:22:50.340 --> 00:22:52.950
Over the last decades,
if you can see the slide,

00:22:52.950 --> 00:22:56.770
the share of people voting
in Democratic elections,

00:22:56.770 --> 00:22:58.890
or presidential elections
that are Democrats,

00:22:58.890 --> 00:23:03.340
are college educated
have grown a lot

00:23:03.340 --> 00:23:06.950
and are now the
majority of voters.

00:23:06.950 --> 00:23:10.580
This radically
altered the leadership

00:23:10.580 --> 00:23:13.080
of at least one party.

00:23:13.080 --> 00:23:18.720
The picture you see above
is congressional leadership.

00:23:18.720 --> 00:23:22.990
So the blue areas represent
leaders in Congress

00:23:22.990 --> 00:23:24.820
who were at one time
very popular, measured

00:23:24.820 --> 00:23:30.876
by when they introduce a bill,
a lot of their colleagues sign

00:23:30.876 --> 00:23:31.376
on.

00:23:31.376 --> 00:23:34.650
It used to be Union County--
the middle of the country.

00:23:34.650 --> 00:23:39.020
But as urbanized professionals
and college educated people

00:23:39.020 --> 00:23:40.900
went to the cities, it split.

00:23:40.900 --> 00:23:45.730
30 years later, the leadership
is now on the coasts,

00:23:45.730 --> 00:23:49.410
think Nancy Pelosi in San
Francisco, Hillary Clinton

00:23:49.410 --> 00:23:50.252
in New York.

00:23:54.260 --> 00:23:58.510
This is how systematically the
people who are most optimistic

00:23:58.510 --> 00:24:00.430
built technologies.

00:24:00.430 --> 00:24:01.780
They made some money.

00:24:01.780 --> 00:24:04.020
They wanted to move to cities.

00:24:04.020 --> 00:24:08.060
They became a majority of
voters and large donors.

00:24:08.060 --> 00:24:10.710
And at least in one
party, it is now

00:24:10.710 --> 00:24:14.020
shifted more towards
that orientation,

00:24:14.020 --> 00:24:16.742
towards a more investment
orientation of government.

00:24:22.070 --> 00:24:24.600
I'll leave why I
think it's going

00:24:24.600 --> 00:24:26.560
to be the most influential.

00:24:26.560 --> 00:24:30.850
This is a map of every
major information

00:24:30.850 --> 00:24:35.194
technology ever invented,
all the way back

00:24:35.194 --> 00:24:35.985
to the Macedonians.

00:24:38.760 --> 00:24:42.260
When I began studying the
history and the philosophy

00:24:42.260 --> 00:24:44.820
of those who invented
big technologies,

00:24:44.820 --> 00:24:49.610
they sounded like
Silicone Valley folks.

00:24:49.610 --> 00:24:53.720
Socrates, who, with
Plato and Aristotle,

00:24:53.720 --> 00:24:58.400
invented the academy, some of
the first official schooling,

00:24:58.400 --> 00:25:01.980
said, there is only
one good, knowledge,

00:25:01.980 --> 00:25:04.830
and one evil, ignorance.

00:25:04.830 --> 00:25:09.570
Socrates was killed
for that belief.

00:25:09.570 --> 00:25:11.520
Centuries later,
Charles Babbage,

00:25:11.520 --> 00:25:14.820
who created one of the first
programmable computers,

00:25:14.820 --> 00:25:17.860
said, knowledge is power.

00:25:17.860 --> 00:25:22.100
Babbage wasn't killed, but
he wasn't a very wealthy man,

00:25:22.100 --> 00:25:23.912
and the government,
at the time, decided

00:25:23.912 --> 00:25:25.120
not to invest in the project.

00:25:25.120 --> 00:25:29.590
They didn't see any
future for a computer.

00:25:29.590 --> 00:25:32.460
Sean Parker, founding
president of Facebook,

00:25:32.460 --> 00:25:36.480
told me it's the hacker
ethic that a lot of problems

00:25:36.480 --> 00:25:39.994
in the world are
information inefficiencies.

00:25:39.994 --> 00:25:40.952
And he's a billionaire.

00:25:43.910 --> 00:25:49.050
The growing complexity
of the world

00:25:49.050 --> 00:25:53.350
will, for the first
time in human history,

00:25:53.350 --> 00:25:59.220
allow this very ancient
ideology to become

00:25:59.220 --> 00:26:05.860
either the most powerful or
a very powerful influence

00:26:05.860 --> 00:26:07.880
over the world.

00:26:07.880 --> 00:26:12.022
And that is where optimists
will inherit the earth.

00:26:12.022 --> 00:26:13.480
MALE SPEAKER:
Through your research

00:26:13.480 --> 00:26:15.650
and through your
interviews, is it

00:26:15.650 --> 00:26:19.320
a matter of the sort of big
voices carrying the most

00:26:19.320 --> 00:26:19.820
weight?

00:26:19.820 --> 00:26:22.690
I'm thinking of the folks
who want to split California

00:26:22.690 --> 00:26:26.870
into six different states--
the Libertarian paradise to be

00:26:26.870 --> 00:26:29.200
established in
international waters.

00:26:29.200 --> 00:26:32.750
How does that impact
the studies you

00:26:32.750 --> 00:26:35.590
found with the overall
progressive mentality

00:26:35.590 --> 00:26:37.930
of the Silicon Valley?

00:26:37.930 --> 00:26:40.060
GREGORY FERENSTEIN:
So I don't know

00:26:40.060 --> 00:26:43.230
where the myth that Silicon
Valley was Libertarian

00:26:43.230 --> 00:26:44.600
came from.

00:26:44.600 --> 00:26:48.410
I suspect it fit into
a kind of narrative,

00:26:48.410 --> 00:26:49.410
speaking as a writer.

00:26:52.080 --> 00:26:54.010
It was easy to say,
OK, these folks don't

00:26:54.010 --> 00:26:56.030
like government regulation.

00:26:56.030 --> 00:26:58.540
And they're big
fans of capitalism.

00:26:58.540 --> 00:27:00.190
And they also like money.

00:27:00.190 --> 00:27:03.610
Therefore they must
be Libertarian.

00:27:03.610 --> 00:27:06.570
And so these kind of
like weird projects,

00:27:06.570 --> 00:27:09.210
like trying to split
California into six states

00:27:09.210 --> 00:27:13.580
or create a floating city
of the coast of California

00:27:13.580 --> 00:27:16.300
that doesn't have any US
government regulation,

00:27:16.300 --> 00:27:17.890
it fit into that narrative.

00:27:17.890 --> 00:27:22.980
And so it was given an
outside voice in the press.

00:27:22.980 --> 00:27:24.960
What you didn't
see was, in fact,

00:27:24.960 --> 00:27:28.100
that almost all donations
from top tech companies

00:27:28.100 --> 00:27:31.050
go to Democrats in
presidential elections.

00:27:31.050 --> 00:27:33.890
So I think what happened was it
was just the media picking up

00:27:33.890 --> 00:27:36.680
on a narrative that wasn't true.

00:27:36.680 --> 00:27:38.280
AUDIENCE: To what
extent do you think

00:27:38.280 --> 00:27:41.380
people are fooling
themselves about knowledge

00:27:41.380 --> 00:27:43.260
and what they really
consider knowledge?

00:27:43.260 --> 00:27:47.510
Like there's a lot
of knowledge in, say,

00:27:47.510 --> 00:27:49.760
the third world that probably
isn't thought about very

00:27:49.760 --> 00:27:51.330
much in Silicon Valley.

00:27:51.330 --> 00:27:53.260
There's knowledge that
is not optimistic,

00:27:53.260 --> 00:27:55.810
say unions are seen
as like complaining.

00:27:55.810 --> 00:27:57.620
So that knowledge seems
to get discounted.

00:27:57.620 --> 00:28:00.460
I think knowledge here
is seen as optimism

00:28:00.460 --> 00:28:03.050
and seen as knowledge that's
around Silicon Valley.

00:28:03.050 --> 00:28:04.540
Do you think that's true?

00:28:04.540 --> 00:28:09.310
Do you think that the knowledge
is really narrower than really

00:28:09.310 --> 00:28:10.660
all knowledge, I guess?

00:28:10.660 --> 00:28:13.020
GREGORY FERENSTEIN: Well, I
think, just philosophically,

00:28:13.020 --> 00:28:15.837
the idea that most
folks, when they

00:28:15.837 --> 00:28:17.920
start a company or at least
