00:30:13.150 --> 00:30:16.920
And that's why solving the
San Francisco housing crisis

00:30:16.920 --> 00:30:21.930
is very core to the technology
political philosophy.

00:30:21.930 --> 00:30:24.890
And I will just say this--
thank you for bringing that up--

00:30:24.890 --> 00:30:29.790
that if you're interested
in solving the crisis,

00:30:29.790 --> 00:30:31.710
you can go to
affordableSanFrancisco.com,

00:30:31.710 --> 00:30:35.340
and I am going to be
helping out with others

00:30:35.340 --> 00:30:38.340
who are doing campaigns to
actually introduce legislation

00:30:38.340 --> 00:30:41.760
that allows San Francisco
to become denser and taller

00:30:41.760 --> 00:30:43.350
and build more quickly.

00:30:43.350 --> 00:30:47.200
AUDIENCE: So you mentioned
the non-zero sum game

00:30:47.200 --> 00:30:50.220
outlook of technologists.

00:30:50.220 --> 00:30:54.920
And for things like material
benefit, health care,

00:30:54.920 --> 00:30:56.340
that is absolutely true.

00:30:56.340 --> 00:30:59.940
But for political power,
there is a fixed amount

00:30:59.940 --> 00:31:03.650
of political decision making
which happens in the world.

00:31:03.650 --> 00:31:08.080
And disparity in political
agency is growing as well.

00:31:08.080 --> 00:31:11.540
This has been complained about
by both the Bernie Sanders

00:31:11.540 --> 00:31:14.200
supporters and the
Donald Trump supporters,

00:31:14.200 --> 00:31:16.060
this growing populist
movement that

00:31:16.060 --> 00:31:20.140
is saying they have no voice
in the governance of the world.

00:31:20.140 --> 00:31:23.980
How do you see the growing
power from the politics

00:31:23.980 --> 00:31:27.810
of the technologists interacting
with this populist movement?

00:31:27.810 --> 00:31:30.410
GREGORY FERENSTEIN: What I
see from the civic sector

00:31:30.410 --> 00:31:34.120
of startups is trying
to empower more voices.

00:31:34.120 --> 00:31:38.720
So if you look at change.org,
Sean Parker's and Matt Mahan's

00:31:38.720 --> 00:31:42.110
brigade, what
they're trying to do

00:31:42.110 --> 00:31:46.000
is build technologies that
allow people with out much money

00:31:46.000 --> 00:31:48.190
to influence politics.

00:31:48.190 --> 00:31:51.110
So change.org-- you don't
need to give any money.

00:31:51.110 --> 00:31:53.000
All you need to do
is sign a petition.

00:31:53.000 --> 00:31:56.820
And if enough people do that,
it gets media attention.

00:31:56.820 --> 00:31:59.230
Some people believe
that helped at least

00:31:59.230 --> 00:32:04.240
influence the Boy Scouts
decision to accept LGBT scout

00:32:04.240 --> 00:32:06.340
leaders.

00:32:06.340 --> 00:32:10.690
So I think it is the hope of
many people in Silicon Valley

00:32:10.690 --> 00:32:15.890
that their technology will
distribute political influence

00:32:15.890 --> 00:32:17.601
more evenly.

00:32:17.601 --> 00:32:19.100
AUDIENCE: What
happens when you talk

00:32:19.100 --> 00:32:22.400
to people who are not in
Silicon Valley about this who

00:32:22.400 --> 00:32:24.270
don't have a favorable view?

00:32:24.270 --> 00:32:26.120
How do they react
to this philosophy,

00:32:26.120 --> 00:32:28.742
and what do they think of it?

00:32:28.742 --> 00:32:31.200
GREGORY FERENSTEIN: So I think--
when I say Silicon Valley,

00:32:31.200 --> 00:32:34.760
I mean kind of a cultural
movement, so broadly urbanized,

00:32:34.760 --> 00:32:36.750
educated professionals.

00:32:36.750 --> 00:32:39.280
That's a lot of people.

00:32:39.280 --> 00:32:44.830
Not everyone agrees with it, and
everyone has their own issues.

00:32:44.830 --> 00:32:46.610
So traditional
Democrats, especially

00:32:46.610 --> 00:32:49.900
out of like the
Bernie Sanders camp,

00:32:49.900 --> 00:32:53.420
fear inequality of any type.

00:32:53.420 --> 00:32:59.330
They think if you are rich and
you're part of a tech company,

00:32:59.330 --> 00:33:01.030
inherently what
you're going to do

00:33:01.030 --> 00:33:04.474
is just try to empower yourself
and screw everyone else.

00:33:04.474 --> 00:33:06.140
And so what they want
to do is they want

00:33:06.140 --> 00:33:08.130
to limit technology companies.

00:33:08.130 --> 00:33:11.290
They want to slow growth,
whether it's Uber and Lyft,

00:33:11.290 --> 00:33:14.360
through regulations
and redistribute

00:33:14.360 --> 00:33:16.560
like power and money.

00:33:16.560 --> 00:33:19.190
That's generally
the reaction I get.

00:33:19.190 --> 00:33:21.250
They do not believe,
or at least they

00:33:21.250 --> 00:33:22.840
have a resistance
to believe, that you

00:33:22.840 --> 00:33:27.100
can be a big corporation
or a widely used product

00:33:27.100 --> 00:33:30.730
and be generally
good for most people.

00:33:30.730 --> 00:33:33.250
Power inherently corrupts.

00:33:33.250 --> 00:33:34.620
That's kind of the orientation.

00:33:34.620 --> 00:33:36.620
And against that, there's
not a lot you can say,

00:33:36.620 --> 00:33:38.330
because to be a
popular tech product,

00:33:38.330 --> 00:33:40.140
you need to be used
by a lot of people.

00:33:40.140 --> 00:33:44.620
To have it be sustainable, it
needs to make a lot of money.

00:33:44.620 --> 00:33:47.070
You can win them
over on some issues,

00:33:47.070 --> 00:33:49.020
like housing in San
Francisco or education,

00:33:49.020 --> 00:33:52.876
if you make education cheaper,
like Udacity and Coursera,

00:33:52.876 --> 00:33:54.750
top universities in the
world which were once

00:33:54.750 --> 00:33:57.490
reserved for very wealthy
people who could afford Stanford

00:33:57.490 --> 00:33:58.420
and Harvard.

00:33:58.420 --> 00:34:00.670
Now everyone can take
their classes for free.

00:34:00.670 --> 00:34:04.080
So I think on some
issues you'll win

00:34:04.080 --> 00:34:07.580
that crowd over--
philosophically probably not,

00:34:07.580 --> 00:34:09.030
but on the issues, yes.

00:34:09.030 --> 00:34:11.874
I don't know if that
answers your question.

00:34:11.874 --> 00:34:15.520
AUDIENCE: What about rural
conservatives, same question?

00:34:15.520 --> 00:34:19.704
GREGORY FERENSTEIN:
Rural conservatives--

00:34:19.704 --> 00:34:21.870
maybe just because I don't
have a lot of touch point

00:34:21.870 --> 00:34:25.250
with rural conservatives,
